We need exactly, but I think it's a good idea to have a look at the source code of the `get_terms()` function. It's in `/wp-includes/taxonomy.php`. You can see that the function calls `apply_filters('get_terms', $terms, $args)` at the end. So you can filter the terms array and remove the terms you don't want to show.

```php
add_filter('get_terms', 'my_get_terms_filter', 10, 2);
function my_get_terms_filter($terms, $args) {
    // Check if we are in the right taxonomy
    if (isset($args['taxonomy']) && $args['taxonomy'] == 'my-taxonomy') {
        foreach ($terms as $key => $term) {
            // Check if term name is in array of terms to exclude
            if (in_array($term->name, array('Term 1', 'Term 2'))) {
                unset($terms[$key]);
            }
        }
    }
    return $terms;
}
```

You can also check if you are in the admin section by using `is_admin()` if you only want to remove the terms from the dropdown there.

**Note:** The filter is called for every taxonomy, so you have to check if you are in the right one. Also, you can check for other parameters` to-behaviour`get_terms() function.

